                  FIrſt, Both ſtand a while, to make the
Preſence of God, and implore his aſſiſtance;
either without ſet form of words;
or with the Pray'r, Prevent we beſeech
Thee, &c. ſecretly.

BEhold the Angels aſſembled in their Quires;
& the bleſſed Saints ready with their Hymns:
behold the Church prepares her ſolemn Offices;
and Summons all her Children to bring in their
prayſes.

That in it we may meet to adore his Greatnes;
and admire the wonders of his infinite
Power.

That we may remember his innumerable Mercies;
and deeply imprint them in the center of
our harts.

Let us empty our heads of all other thoughts;
and prepare that upper room to entertain our
God.

Why ſhould we thus neglect that ſacred Science;
and be buſie in every thing but our own
Salvation?

Pauſe a while; to reflect on what you
have ſaid, and to renew your attention;
then begin Lauds.

He made the Angels meſſengers of his victory;
and vouchſaf't even himſelf to bring us the joyful
news:

To convince thy followers into this bleſt belief;
and ſettle in their harts a firm ground of
hope.

Leaving thy deareſt bleſſing on their heads;
and promiſing them a Comforter to ſupply thine
abſence.

What though we mourn and be afflicted here;
and ſigh under the miſeries of this world for a
time?

He is riſen, and made the light his Garment;
and commanded the Clouds to be the chariot of
his triumph:

May all created nature adore thy Power;
and the Church of thy Redeem'd exult in thy
goodnes:

Be Thou the principal ſubject of our ſtudyes;
and dayly entertainment of our moſt ſerious
thoughts:

Draw us up to Thee on thy Throne of blyſs;
that we may ſee thy face, and rejoyce with
Thee for ever in thy Kingdom.

A place of joy and everlaſting fruition;
where we ſhal love and poſſeſs and delight in
Him for ever:

How ſhal we all rejoyce in one anothers felicity;
but infinitely more in the infinitely greater
felicity of God!

O light! ſhine thou perpetually in our eys;


that thy brightnes may darken the falſe luſtre of
this world:

Praiſe him in the vaſt immenſity of his power;


Praiſe him in the admirable wiſdom of his
Providence:

Let them fill up their time with other imployments;
who think thy rewards not worth their
labour.

Thy manſions are built with choiceſt jewels;
and the pavement of thy ſtreets is tranſparent
gold,

Behold the felicities to which we are cal'd;
and where can we meet ſuch pleaſures to entertain
us?

Thou tel'ſt us ſtill of incomparably higher delights;
harken, O my ſoul, and humbly adore
thy God.

Whoſe bounty has provided thee large rewards;
Since they are no leſs then his very
Self.

What is it, glorious Lord, to ſee thy face;
but to know Thee as thou art in thine own bleſt
Being?

To know the Goodnes of the Holy Ghoſt;
and the incomprehenſible Glorys of the undivided
Trinity.

Me thinks they turn to ſubſtance as they go;
and I feel them ſtir and work through all my
powers.

Me thinks they ly as a Cordial at my hart;
and ſend forth ſpirits to quicken and refreſh
me.

Never intermedling with the actions of others;


unleſs where reaſon and charity engage
'em.

Thy pity may grieve, and thy charity indeavour;
but if they will not hear, follow thou
thy God.

MEeknes indeed, is the heav'n of this life;
but the heav'n of heav'ns, O Lord, is above
with Thee.

But to be fully happy, we muſt ſtay till hereafter;
till thy mercy bring us to our laſt great
end.



O my adored JESUS! let me love thee always;
* becauſe from eternity thou haſt loved
